<article>
    <h1>CANTAPP: THE GEN&#xAD;ERAL PRO&#xAD;LOGUE &#x2013; AN EDI&#xAD;TION IN AN APP</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200731/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-31"><time>2020-07-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Ac­tor-di­rec­tor Terry Jones was best known as one of the mem­bers of the leg­endary Monty Python com­edy team. But he was also a me­di­ae­val scholar who pub­lished two books about Chaucer and his works. This app, which reads Chaucer’s The Can­ter­bury Tales in Mid­dle English, was the last big aca­demic pro­ject Jones worked on be­fore his death in Jan­uary at age 77.</p>
    <p>It is a rather dis­con­cert­ing ex­pe­ri­ence to first hear Mid­dle English, as the pro­nun­ci­a­tion is at once fa­mil­iar and for­eign. The desk­top ver­sion (right) of the app is the best, as the text in both the orig­i­nal Mid­dle English and mod­ern trans­la­tion pops up in karaoke fash­ion so you can read as you lis­ten.</p>
    <p>But if you are an ad­ven­tur­ous soul, you could just wing it on the mo­bile app, avail­able on both Ap­ple and An­droid plat­forms.</p>
    <p>This is part of an in­ter­na­tional pro­ject spear­headed by Univer­sity of Saskatchew­an English pro­fes­sor Peter Robin­son, and ap­par­ently the team has enough ma­te­rial for two more apps. So Chaucer fans and tor­tured stu­dents can look for­ward to The Miller’s Tale next.</p>
    <p>WHERE: Web­site (str.sg/JeyZ), App Store (str.sg/Jeyo), Google Play (str.sg/JeyJ)</p>
    <p>AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>

